CHRIS MANNING: Do you have
a favorite oyster place

00:21:11.310 --> 00:21:13.050
that you used to go for them?

00:21:13.050 --> 00:21:15.508
SUMMER BRENNAN: Well, actually,
I love Grand Central Oyster

00:21:15.508 --> 00:21:17.800
Bar in Midtown.

00:21:17.800 --> 00:21:19.380
When I work at the
UN, it's close by.

00:21:19.380 --> 00:21:21.000
So it's a nice place
on the way home to--

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:22.250
CHRIS MANNING:
How about locally?

00:21:22.250 --> 00:21:23.210
SUMMER BRENNAN: Yeah?

00:21:23.210 --> 00:21:24.660
Oh, locally?

00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:26.180
I think my favorite--
well, I don't

00:21:26.180 --> 00:21:28.720
want to-- they're all great.

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:31.320
I like all the oyster farms.

00:21:31.320 --> 00:21:33.892
I especially like Hog
Island Oyster's sweetwaters.

00:21:33.892 --> 00:21:36.350
Hog Island sweetwaters, I think
that's what they're called.

00:21:36.350 --> 00:21:37.100
They're excellent.

00:21:37.100 --> 00:21:41.030
If you haven't them,
definitely give it a try.

00:21:41.030 --> 00:21:42.122
CHRIS MANNING: Cool.

00:21:42.122 --> 00:21:44.080
Does anybody in the
audience have any questions

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:45.070
they'd like to ask Summer?

00:21:45.070 --> 00:21:45.569
Great.

00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:50.765
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:21:50.765 --> 00:21:51.556
SUMMER BRENNAN: Hi.

00:21:51.556 --> 00:21:53.532
AUDIENCE: Thanks so
much for being here.

00:21:53.532 --> 00:21:54.532
It was great to see you.

00:21:57.508 --> 00:22:00.484
I lived in [INAUDIBLE]
from 2008 to 2012,

00:22:00.484 --> 00:22:03.956
and I came to a couple of town
halls, and I knew some people.

00:22:03.956 --> 00:22:06.684
And whenever people asked
me about the story, what's

00:22:06.684 --> 00:22:10.440
happening, I would be like, I
don't even know where to start.

00:22:10.440 --> 00:22:12.430
It's so complicated.

00:22:12.430 --> 00:22:13.730
And I'm curious.

00:22:13.730 --> 00:22:18.950
Even today, you presented most
of your thoughts as questions.

00:22:18.950 --> 00:22:20.918
It's just something that
we're grappling with.

00:22:20.918 --> 00:22:22.394
It's really hard to understand.

00:22:22.394 --> 00:22:24.066
So I'm curious--
I'm looking forward

00:22:24.066 --> 00:22:26.822
to buying your book today--
how you lay the story out

00:22:26.822 --> 00:22:30.810
and how you decided
is it chronological?

00:22:30.810 --> 00:22:34.580
SUMMER BRENNAN: So it jumps
around a little, actually.

00:22:34.580 --> 00:22:37.470
And I tried to think of it
in the planning of the story.

00:22:37.470 --> 00:22:40.020
Well, first, I actually laid
everything out chronologically

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:40.670
in my notes.

00:22:40.670 --> 00:22:44.390
So I made a massive timeline
that was like 8,000 BC,

00:22:44.390 --> 00:22:46.300
Miwoks settle in Olema.

00:22:46.300 --> 00:22:49.520
And then the most
recent was January 1st,

00:22:49.520 --> 00:22:50.620
oyster farm is gone.

00:22:50.620 --> 00:22:52.280
And then included
within that timeline

00:22:52.280 --> 00:22:55.540
was everybody's birthdays and
death dates and everything.

00:22:55.540 --> 00:22:56.890
And then I switched it around.

00:22:56.890 --> 00:22:58.460
So your question
was chronological.

00:22:58.460 --> 00:23:00.529
It's quite chronological
towards the end,

00:23:00.529 --> 00:23:02.570
because it sort of just
is the momentum of moving

00:23:02.570 --> 00:23:04.504
through this story,
where it's local,

00:23:04.504 --> 00:23:06.920
and suddenly, you've got Koch
brother attorneys coming in,

00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:10.355
and the Supreme Court,
and then all these people.

00:23:10.355 --> 00:23:12.730
But it does jump around a
bit, and you going along

00:23:12.730 --> 00:23:14.380
chronologically,
and then I step back

00:23:14.380 --> 00:23:18.009
to Sir Francis Drake at the
beginning of the next section.

00:23:18.009 --> 00:23:20.300
AUDIENCE: What would you say
the lasting impact of this

00:23:20.300 --> 00:23:23.200
has been on the
community in Port Reyes?

00:23:23.200 --> 00:23:25.500
SUMMER BRENNAN: Oh gosh.

00:23:25.500 --> 00:23:28.190
Well, I think that's still
being figured out to a degree.

00:23:28.190 --> 00:23:32.010
It's still a very hotly
contested, debated issue.

00:23:32.010 --> 00:23:34.340
And with the book coming
out, it's flared up,

00:23:34.340 --> 00:23:36.510
and there's been some angry
things in the newspaper

00:23:36.510 --> 00:23:39.550
and people that violently
dislike the book,

00:23:39.550 --> 00:23:42.570
and other people that are
absolutely thrilled with it.

00:23:42.570 --> 00:23:46.640
So locally, I think it has
created some lasting divisions

00:23:46.640 --> 00:23:51.040
between some people in
the agricultural community

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:53.380
and in the
environmental community.

00:23:53.380 --> 00:23:55.780
There's some trust
that's been lost there.

00:23:58.320 --> 00:24:00.220
And with the National
Park too, people

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:02.540
that feel that they
handled this very badly,

00:24:02.540 --> 00:24:05.630
they're nervous about
anything that they do.

00:24:05.630 --> 00:24:08.890
So there's other issues popping
up with Tule elk management

00:24:08.890 --> 00:24:11.416
and different things that
require public input that I

00:24:11.416 --> 00:24:15.700
think that they're
trying to soothe over,

00:24:15.700 --> 00:24:21.154
but those tensions are
still felt, I think.

00:24:21.154 --> 00:24:21.978
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:24:21.978 --> 00:24:22.390
SUMMER BRENNAN: Hi.

00:24:22.390 --> 00:24:24.780
AUDIENCE: So I guess my
question is from maybe a broader

00:24:24.780 --> 00:24:25.380
perspective.

00:24:25.380 --> 00:24:27.290
Throughout the course
of your research,

00:24:27.290 --> 00:24:28.820
obviously, one of
the like the core

00:24:28.820 --> 00:24:32.490
tenets that we're grappling
with is the rise of agriculture

00:24:32.490 --> 00:24:35.990
and how that fits in
with our environment.

00:24:35.990 --> 00:24:38.422
Were you optimistic
as you learned more

00:24:38.422 --> 00:24:39.755
about modern farming techniques?

00:24:39.755 --> 00:24:41.160
And do you feel
like these two are

00:24:41.160 --> 00:24:42.951
going to be able to
reconcile in the future

00:24:42.951 --> 00:24:47.980
where we can have a successful
and large society that

00:24:47.980 --> 00:24:49.760
reconciles with our environment?

00:24:49.760 --> 00:24:52.530
SUMMER BRENNAN: Yeah, I
mean, I work with this stuff

00:24:52.530 --> 00:24:53.920
a little bit with
the UN as well.

00:24:53.920 --> 00:24:59.520
And I think what's encouraging
is that we have the technology

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:00.980
to do all these
things sustainably,

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:03.030
even our energy production
and transportation.

00:25:03.030 --> 00:25:04.530
It's just a question
of implementing

00:25:04.530 --> 00:25:07.140
the systems is my take on it.

00:25:07.140 --> 00:25:09.240
And that's the same with
agriculture as well.

00:25:09.240 --> 00:25:11.850
So there's different obstacles
to that, and some of them

00:25:11.850 --> 00:25:13.964
are finances.

00:25:13.964 --> 00:25:15.380
And at other times,
there are just

00:25:15.380 --> 00:25:17.199
people that are in
powerful positions,

00:25:17.199 --> 00:25:19.490
or they have industries that
they don't want to see go.

00:25:19.490 --> 00:25:22.600
So that's where
you run into-- it's

00:25:22.600 --> 00:25:24.880
hard to make that
transition, I think.

00:25:24.880 --> 00:25:28.000
So it's technically possible.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:31.300
I just hope that we can make it
economically possible as well.

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:35.660
And this was a lot about
fisheries, the agriculture,

00:25:35.660 --> 00:25:36.790
but it's an oyster farm.

00:25:36.790 --> 00:25:38.840
So I had to look a lot at that.

00:25:38.840 --> 00:25:40.430
And I we do need to
drastically change

00:25:40.430 --> 00:25:45.780
how we handle fishing and
seafood, because fish stocks,

00:25:45.780 --> 00:25:47.880
I think, are projected
to collapse in 50 years

00:25:47.880 --> 00:25:49.190
if we don't change.

00:25:49.190 --> 00:25:51.134
So I hope we can change that.

00:25:51.134 --> 00:25:53.550
CHRIS MANNING: I'd be interested
in how your for at the UN

00:25:53.550 --> 00:25:55.180
has also influenced
some of the stuff

00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:57.250
that you were able to
write in this story.

00:25:57.250 --> 00:25:59.070
Did you find that to
be the case at all?

00:25:59.070 --> 00:26:00.420
Maybe the systems thinking part?

00:26:00.420 --> 00:26:02.253
SUMMER BRENNAN: I think
it helped me to take

00:26:02.253 --> 00:26:03.529
a bit of a step back from it.

00:26:03.529 --> 00:26:05.070
Working as a reporter
in Point Reyes,

00:26:05.070 --> 00:26:08.790
I started in 2012, so I
guess you were still there.

00:26:08.790 --> 00:26:12.645
You know, you can get a little
myopic about the whole thing,

00:26:12.645 --> 00:26:14.520
but when you step back
and look at the bigger

00:26:14.520 --> 00:26:16.740
picture in the context of
climate change, and ocean

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:19.140
acidification, and even just
in conflicts in general.

00:26:19.140 --> 00:26:22.310
In the book, I compare it to the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict,

00:26:22.310 --> 00:26:24.100
which some people
think is kind of funny.

00:26:24.100 --> 00:26:27.090
Leonard Lopate laughed about
that when I was on his show.

00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:29.120
But it did remind
me of that in a way.

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:32.070
You can see that any time you're
in conflict about something,

00:26:32.070 --> 00:26:35.440
especially if it's over
land, the same things

00:26:35.440 --> 00:26:36.480
come up again and again.

00:26:36.480 --> 00:26:38.882
So yeah, I think it
really helped me,

00:26:38.882 --> 00:26:41.340
especially since it was such
a personal story, to step back

00:26:41.340 --> 00:26:44.270
a little bit and see
it for the themes that

00:26:44.270 --> 00:26:47.620
are recurring issues.

00:26:47.620 --> 00:26:50.270
CHRIS MANNING: Any other
questions in the audience?

00:26:50.270 --> 00:26:53.620
AUDIENCE: I guess my perspective
of the Wilderness Act,

00:26:53.620 --> 00:26:55.730
or my understanding
of the intent

00:26:55.730 --> 00:26:58.820
there is that it
protects areas such

00:26:58.820 --> 00:27:00.330
that there's no human activity.

00:27:00.330 --> 00:27:02.710
It belongs to nature.

00:27:02.710 --> 00:27:07.710
And the primary thing
that it prevents against

00:27:07.710 --> 00:27:15.110
is any sort of man-made building
or man-made-- and commerce,

00:27:15.110 --> 00:27:16.760
that's definitely very man-made.

00:27:16.760 --> 00:27:20.430
And commerce has a huge
impact on the environment.

00:27:20.430 --> 00:27:26.865
So I was curious, one,
what your perspective was,

00:27:26.865 --> 00:27:28.490
because it sounded
like you had changed

00:27:28.490 --> 00:27:33.245
your perspective over time
through working in a newspaper

00:27:33.245 --> 00:27:34.560
and what not.

00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:39.480
But also broadly, is my
understanding of the Wilderness

00:27:39.480 --> 00:27:40.625
Act, am I wrong there?

00:27:40.625 --> 00:27:42.000
SUMMER BRENNAN:
No, you're right.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.669
So the Wilderness Act, the
language is a little poetic.

00:27:44.669 --> 00:27:46.710
I'm going to misquote it
here, but it's something

00:27:46.710 --> 00:27:49.650
along the lines
of a wilderness is

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:53.530
an area where the works
of man are not dominant.

00:27:53.530 --> 00:27:58.160
It's where the community
of nature is untrampled

00:27:58.160 --> 00:28:00.140
and where man is a visitor
but does not remain.

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:02.600
So that's a mangled
version of that line.

00:28:02.600 --> 00:28:05.196
But you're absolutely right.

00:28:05.196 --> 00:28:07.239
It's that it's set
aside not for mankind.

00:28:07.239 --> 00:28:07.780
We can visit.

00:28:07.780 --> 00:28:10.369
We can go take a hike there,
but we can't ride our mountain

00:28:10.369 --> 00:28:12.160
bikes, and there's not
supposed to be road,

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:13.370
not supposed to be buildings,
definitely not supposed

00:28:13.370 --> 00:28:14.465
to be private businesses.

00:28:17.796 --> 00:28:18.670
So I agree with that.

00:28:18.670 --> 00:28:20.140
So that is what the
Wilderness Act was saying.

00:28:20.140 --> 00:28:21.870
And when wilderness
is designated,

00:28:21.870 --> 00:28:24.200
that is the purpose.

00:28:24.200 --> 00:28:27.272
Along with that,
when that happened,

00:28:27.272 --> 00:28:29.105
there were also writings
that spoke about it

00:28:29.105 --> 00:28:34.900
in an idenic, humanless way
that other academics and critics

00:28:34.900 --> 00:28:38.070
have argued erased and dismiss
the indigenous people that

00:28:38.070 --> 00:28:39.090
were living here.

00:28:39.090 --> 00:28:42.780
So I agree with what the
Wilderness Act says and sets

00:28:42.780 --> 00:28:44.490
aside.

00:28:44.490 --> 00:28:46.540
And I think that it can
be only strengthened

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:49.320
by acknowledging the
state of this land

00:28:49.320 --> 00:28:52.440
before Europeans came
and colonized it.

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:56.160
Because I think those arguments
have been used to undermine it.

00:28:56.160 --> 00:28:58.570
I feel there's been an
incomplete reevaluation

00:28:58.570 --> 00:29:02.940
of our older wilderness ideas.

00:29:02.940 --> 00:29:05.140
A positive reexamination
of those begins by saying,

00:29:05.140 --> 00:29:06.556
well, just remember,
when you talk

00:29:06.556 --> 00:29:08.860
about it being a landscape
where man isn't dominant,

00:29:08.860 --> 00:29:11.730
there were people living here.

00:29:11.730 --> 00:29:13.030
And that's true.

00:29:13.030 --> 00:29:16.550
And part of, not wilderness,
but national parks

00:29:16.550 --> 00:29:21.144
do protect cultural, historic
areas and things like that.

00:29:21.144 --> 00:29:22.810
But anyway, I don't
know if that answers

00:29:22.810 --> 00:29:25.940
your question a little bit,
but it's both of those things.

00:29:25.940 --> 00:29:28.480
And I think it actually is
set aside not for people.

00:29:28.480 --> 00:29:31.024
But we also need to
acknowledge that there

00:29:31.024 --> 00:29:32.940
were people living here,
and you can't pretend

00:29:32.940 --> 00:29:35.180
that that wasn't the case.

00:29:35.180 --> 00:29:38.270
But we have to preserve
them, because there's people

00:29:38.270 --> 00:29:38.770
everywhere.

00:29:38.770 --> 00:29:40.980
And we do need to set aside
some places that are just

00:29:40.980 --> 00:29:43.940
for natural ecosystems
to prepare them or let

00:29:43.940 --> 00:29:45.305
them be intact.

00:29:45.305 --> 00:29:46.680
AUDIENCE: Was
there actually case

00:29:46.680 --> 00:29:50.987
in this story where Native
Americans were farming oysters?

00:29:50.987 --> 00:29:53.570
SUMMER BRENNAN: No, actually,
as I found researching the book,

00:29:53.570 --> 00:29:55.810
there were not
native populations

00:29:55.810 --> 00:29:59.160
of oysters in the Bay Area,
at least as recently as

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:00.780
like over 1,000 years ago.

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:03.770
And I'd thought that there'd
been all these native oysters

00:30:03.770 --> 00:30:05.750
in San Francisco Bay,
but actually they

00:30:05.750 --> 00:30:09.426
were imported from
Washington, and New York,

00:30:09.426 --> 00:30:10.800
and other parts
of the East Coast

00:30:10.800 --> 00:30:14.670
by oyster businessmen
around the Gold Rush.

00:30:14.670 --> 00:30:16.830
So that's in here too.

00:30:16.830 --> 00:30:19.610
So there aren't any stories
of Native Americans harvesting

00:30:19.610 --> 00:30:22.020
oysters, per se-- other things.

00:30:22.020 --> 00:30:26.690
So I did talk to the chief
of the local tribe that

00:30:26.690 --> 00:30:29.480
once lived in that area, and
it was really interesting.

00:30:29.480 --> 00:30:33.180
Because he's a modern person
with modern businesses,

00:30:33.180 --> 00:30:37.410
and yet, is tasked with carrying
on this spiritual heritage

00:30:37.410 --> 00:30:38.350
of the place as well.

00:30:38.350 --> 00:30:40.266
And so that was a really
interesting dichotomy

00:30:40.266 --> 00:30:41.550
to encounter.

00:30:41.550 --> 00:30:43.640
So I tried to incorporate
as many of those voices

00:30:43.640 --> 00:30:45.430
as I could.

00:30:45.430 --> 00:30:47.470
AUDIENCE: Are there any
similar cases to this

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:51.110
anywhere else in North America
or the rest of the world?

00:30:51.110 --> 00:30:55.270
SUMMER BRENNAN: Well,
to this particular case,

00:30:55.270 --> 00:30:56.450
not to my knowledge.

00:30:56.450 --> 00:30:58.210
But there are
instances everywhere

00:30:58.210 --> 00:31:01.010
where they have tried to
pry open protected areas

00:31:01.010 --> 00:31:02.590
for different reasons.

00:31:02.590 --> 00:31:05.440
We have people following the
news with the Arctic right now.

00:31:05.440 --> 00:31:06.900
That's just with whether
that'll be wilderness

00:31:06.900 --> 00:31:07.691
or what's going on.

00:31:07.691 --> 00:31:12.440
So I didn't find a case
that was really like this.

00:31:12.440 --> 00:31:15.382
There was an issue with
an Indian trader outpost

00:31:15.382 --> 00:31:16.840
that people compared
this to, where

00:31:16.840 --> 00:31:18.084
he was in a national park.

00:31:18.084 --> 00:31:19.750
But it wasn't a
wilderness area, so it's

00:31:19.750 --> 00:31:22.849
a bit of a different story.

00:31:22.849 --> 00:31:24.640
AUDIENCE: It sounded
like this actually did

00:31:24.640 --> 00:31:25.950
go through the court system.

00:31:25.950 --> 00:31:27.560
SUMMER BRENNAN: Yes, it did.

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:29.190
AUDIENCE: It seems
conceptually like it

00:31:29.190 --> 00:31:31.430
should be a pretty--
legally, it seems

00:31:31.430 --> 00:31:33.000
like it if it's
in the wilderness,

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:34.510
it shouldn't be allowed.

00:31:34.510 --> 00:31:38.700
The contract expired, and
so the contract's finished.

00:31:38.700 --> 00:31:41.860
Was there any more legal
precedent that was set,

00:31:41.860 --> 00:31:44.272
or was the court
case mostly just?

00:31:44.272 --> 00:31:45.730
SUMMER BRENNAN:
Well, I mean, to be

00:31:45.730 --> 00:31:48.230
spoilers-- I guess you can see
this in the news-- the oyster

00:31:48.230 --> 00:31:49.740
farm was shut down,
and they did not

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:50.989
compromise the Wilderness Act.

00:31:50.989 --> 00:31:53.249
So it did go through
the courts, and they

00:31:53.249 --> 00:31:55.290
did petition the Supreme
Court, but they said no.

00:31:55.290 --> 00:31:58.980
So it almost went is as high
as it could, but it didn't.

00:31:58.980 --> 00:32:01.520
Many people agree with you that
it was absolutely clear-cut,

00:32:01.520 --> 00:32:03.090
and it was only a lot
of smoke and mirrors

00:32:03.090 --> 00:32:04.423
that confused it in the process.

00:32:07.450 --> 00:32:09.470
Because it was
designated in '76 as

00:32:09.470 --> 00:32:10.960
wilderness, and
the '64 Wilderness

00:32:10.960 --> 00:32:13.406
Act dictates what wilderness is.

00:32:13.406 --> 00:32:15.030
But there was confusion
in the process.

00:32:15.030 --> 00:32:17.020
Not everybody agreed on
what wilderness means,

00:32:17.020 --> 00:32:18.561
and that's why I
thought that getting

00:32:18.561 --> 00:32:19.962
at the core of
what is wilderness

00:32:19.962 --> 00:32:21.670
was such an important
issue in this book.

00:32:21.670 --> 00:32:24.130
Because you had Senator
Dianne Feinstein writing

00:32:24.130 --> 00:32:25.970
in defense of the
oyster farm, saying this

00:32:25.970 --> 00:32:27.200
is not a wilderness area.

00:32:27.200 --> 00:32:29.110
Even though it had
been designated as one

00:32:29.110 --> 00:32:32.160
36 years prior, she said this
is not a remote wilderness.

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:34.916
There's cattle ranches and
dairy firms on all sides.

00:32:34.916 --> 00:32:36.665
It's such and such
close to San Francisco.

00:32:36.665 --> 00:32:38.210
It doesn't count.

00:32:38.210 --> 00:32:40.260
And so that was what
was interesting to me.

00:32:40.260 --> 00:32:41.570
Who decides what's wilderness?

00:32:41.570 --> 00:32:43.069
And why does it
count as wilderness?

00:32:45.125 --> 00:32:47.500
And that's why I think it is
such an important case going

00:32:47.500 --> 00:32:49.475
forward, that you can't
just come and say,

00:32:49.475 --> 00:32:51.350
well, actually this
place is a bit messed up,

00:32:51.350 --> 00:32:55.220
so let's just scrap the whole
wilderness thing about it

00:32:55.220 --> 00:32:56.030
and take it away.

00:32:56.030 --> 00:32:57.162
So that was the argument.

00:32:57.162 --> 00:32:58.620
OK, well, we said
it is wilderness,

00:32:58.620 --> 00:33:00.260
but maybe we should
take that back,

00:33:00.260 --> 00:33:04.510
because on second thought,
maybe not so much.

00:33:04.510 --> 00:33:06.600
But it is wilderness.

00:33:06.600 --> 00:33:08.022
They won.

00:33:08.022 --> 00:33:10.480
CHRIS MANNING: So when the
Lunny family took over-- Is that

00:33:10.480 --> 00:33:10.790
how you say it?

00:33:10.790 --> 00:33:10.860
The Lunny?

00:33:10.860 --> 00:33:11.650
SUMMER BRENNAN: The Lunny, yeah.

00:33:11.650 --> 00:33:14.149
CHRIS MANNING: Yeah, the Lunny
family took over in, I think,

00:33:14.149 --> 00:33:15.130
2005, was it?

00:33:15.130 --> 00:33:16.880
SUMMER BRENNAN: Yeah,
sale closed in 2005.

00:33:16.880 --> 00:33:18.296
CHRIS MANNING: Was
it their intent

00:33:18.296 --> 00:33:20.130
to fight that concept
of the wilderness, or?

00:33:20.130 --> 00:33:21.629
SUMMER BRENNAN: I
don't know if they

00:33:21.629 --> 00:33:23.660
wanted to fight the
concept of the wilderness.

00:33:23.660 --> 00:33:28.560
I know that they grew up-- Kevin
Lunny, who bought the farm,

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:29.830
grew up next door.

00:33:29.830 --> 00:33:32.817
And his goal seemed to
be that he would really

00:33:32.817 --> 00:33:34.400
work to clean up the
farm, and then it

00:33:34.400 --> 00:33:35.380
would be able to continue.

00:33:35.380 --> 00:33:36.820
It was a very
lucrative business.

00:33:36.820 --> 00:33:39.100
I mean, recently, they
mentioned that last year, I

00:33:39.100 --> 00:33:41.300
believe, the oyster farm
made about $5 million,

00:33:41.300 --> 00:33:44.184
which isn't huge,
but it's a lot.

00:33:44.184 --> 00:33:45.100
It's more than I make.

00:33:47.730 --> 00:33:49.340
So there's a lot of
initiatives, and I

00:33:49.340 --> 00:33:51.340
know that they were really
fond of the business.

00:33:51.340 --> 00:33:53.410
And I think it seems
at their motivations,

00:33:53.410 --> 00:33:54.530
they thought if
they could just show

00:33:54.530 --> 00:33:56.000
that they were good
environmental stewards-- which

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:57.610
is why there were so many
fights about the science.

00:33:57.610 --> 00:33:58.790
It's that they were
accused of being

00:33:58.790 --> 00:33:59.910
poor environmental stewards.

00:33:59.910 --> 00:34:00.940
They were like, how
can you say that?

00:34:00.940 --> 00:34:03.260
We're working so hard
to clean up this area.

00:34:03.260 --> 00:34:06.532
Because their predecessors had
a lot of environmental problems,

00:34:06.532 --> 00:34:08.490
which I was really shocked,
the more research I

00:34:08.490 --> 00:34:10.215
did, how extensive they were.

00:34:10.215 --> 00:34:11.465
So they had a lot to clean up.

00:34:11.465 --> 00:34:13.862
I think they just got
in over their head.

00:34:13.862 --> 00:34:15.820
CHRIS MANNING: Any thoughts
for your next book?

00:34:15.820 --> 00:34:16.510
Is that even--

00:34:16.510 --> 00:34:18.676
SUMMER BRENNAN: I don't
know if I can talk about it.

00:34:18.676 --> 00:34:20.850
So I do have a couple
things I've been working on.

00:34:20.850 --> 00:34:24.420
I joked on Twitter about novel,
but don't hold your breath.

00:34:24.420 --> 00:34:27.100
But I have a couple
nonfiction projects

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:29.826
that have been in the works,
that I pitched to my agent,

00:34:29.826 --> 00:34:30.909
but not to any publishers.

00:34:30.909 --> 00:34:34.309
So we'll see what
gets picked up next.

00:34:34.309 --> 00:34:35.850
CHRIS MANNING: You
think nonfiction's

00:34:35.850 --> 00:34:37.840
a medium that you're going to
stick with for a little bit?

00:34:37.840 --> 00:34:39.215
SUMMER BRENNAN:
I really love it.

00:34:39.215 --> 00:34:40.449
I love research.

00:34:40.449 --> 00:34:42.817
I made a joke that
I could probably

00:34:42.817 --> 00:34:44.400
write about research
libraries the way

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:46.699
some people write love poems.

00:34:46.699 --> 00:34:48.030
And so that excites me.

00:34:48.030 --> 00:34:49.570
And I like historical stuff.

00:34:49.570 --> 00:34:54.920
So both of my next projects
are very historically based.

00:34:54.920 --> 00:34:56.840
One of my favorite
writers is Erik Larson,

00:34:56.840 --> 00:34:58.506
and I think he does
just a wonderful job

00:34:58.506 --> 00:35:01.030
of finding all this great,
rich historical detail,

00:35:01.030 --> 00:35:02.397
and telling it like a novel.

00:35:02.397 --> 00:35:04.230
And so I'd like to get
better at doing that.

00:35:04.230 --> 00:35:04.560
That's my plan.

00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:05.518
CHRIS MANNING: Awesome.

00:35:05.518 --> 00:35:06.870
Definitely a need for it.

00:35:06.870 --> 00:35:11.460
AUDIENCE: In an ideal
world, or if you didn't

00:35:11.460 --> 00:35:13.540
have to pay attention
to the legislation

00:35:13.540 --> 00:35:15.170
or what not, what
do you think would

00:35:15.170 --> 00:35:19.055
have been-- in your opinion,
what would you have done?

00:35:19.055 --> 00:35:20.930
SUMMER BRENNAN: If I
was the deciding person?

00:35:20.930 --> 00:35:22.346
AUDIENCE: If you
were the decider,

00:35:22.346 --> 00:35:25.170
and there was no law that
you had to pay attention to.

00:35:25.170 --> 00:35:28.090
SUMMER BRENNAN: So if there
was no wilderness designation?

00:35:28.090 --> 00:35:29.590
See, that's an
interesting question.

00:35:29.590 --> 00:35:32.712
Because if there wasn't a
wilderness designation--

00:35:32.712 --> 00:35:34.420
I'm avoiding your
question a little bit--

00:35:34.420 --> 00:35:36.830
I heard other people
argue that there's

00:35:36.830 --> 00:35:39.670
no reason why the farm couldn't
have existed peacefully

00:35:39.670 --> 00:35:42.560
as long as they always
followed the regulations.

00:35:42.560 --> 00:35:44.340
My observation is that
they did not always

00:35:44.340 --> 00:35:46.690
follow the regulations, and
that it's very difficult

00:35:46.690 --> 00:35:48.669
to make all of your
employees follow the rules

00:35:48.669 --> 00:35:50.960
and understand why you have
to follow particular rules,

00:35:50.960 --> 00:35:53.022
because sometimes they
don't seem logical to you.

00:35:53.022 --> 00:35:54.980
And you can say, look,
I know this environment.

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:55.930
I know what it needs.

00:35:55.930 --> 00:35:57.840
But you're not always right.

00:35:57.840 --> 00:35:58.960
So it's tricky.

00:35:58.960 --> 00:36:01.970
So I don't know.

00:36:01.970 --> 00:36:02.470
It's hard.

00:36:02.470 --> 00:36:04.650
I mean, being a
local too, it was

00:36:04.650 --> 00:36:06.960
very scary to come up
against information

00:36:06.960 --> 00:36:09.650
that made it suggest maybe
the farm should have gone.

00:36:09.650 --> 00:36:11.941
Because you know you're going
to get a lot of pushback.

00:36:11.941 --> 00:36:14.580
But that was the impression
that I got by the end.

00:36:14.580 --> 00:36:17.300
So I feel that the farm
itself, the infrastructure,

00:36:17.300 --> 00:36:20.134
just wasn't environmentally
sound enough.

00:36:20.134 --> 00:36:21.800
If they could have
completely restarted,

00:36:21.800 --> 00:36:24.480
had tons of money to just pull
everything out of the estuary

00:36:24.480 --> 00:36:27.200
and start over from scratch with
this totally green operation

00:36:27.200 --> 00:36:31.660
that didn't have the decades
of environmental issues

00:36:31.660 --> 00:36:33.750
and no wilderness
designation, and nobody ever

00:36:33.750 --> 00:36:36.110
goes near the baby seals,
and, all that stuff,

00:36:36.110 --> 00:36:38.200
they maybe could have
worked something out.

00:36:38.200 --> 00:36:41.310
But unfortunately, that whole
scenario just wasn't the case.

00:36:41.310 --> 00:36:43.560
CHRIS MANNING: Thanks so
much, Summer, for joining us.

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:44.979
And thanks for coming to Google.

00:36:44.979 --> 00:36:46.270
SUMMER BRENNAN: Thanks so much.

00:36:46.270 --> 00:36:47.210
CHRIS MANNING: Everybody
go buy the book

00:36:47.210 --> 00:36:49.900
if you haven't already,
and support Summer's work.

00:36:49.900 --> 00:36:50.900
It's great.

00:36:50.900 --> 00:36:51.640
Thank you.

00:36:51.640 --> 00:36:52.931
SUMMER BRENNAN: Thanks so much.

